# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: ascii
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:ascii/0-number] As a numerical digit, 0 plays a crucial role in decimal notation: it indicates that the power of ten corresponding to the place containing a 0 does not contribute to the total.
[src:ascii/0-number] For example, "205" in decimal means two hundreds, no tens, and five ones.
[src:ascii/0-number] The same principle applies in place-value notations that uses a base other than ten, such as binary and hexadecimal.
[src:ascii/0-number] The modern use of 0 in this manner derives from Indian mathematics that was transmitted to Europe via medieval Islamic mathematicians and popularized by Fibonacci.
[src:ascii/0-number] Common names for the number 0 in English include *zero*, *nought*, *naught* (/nɔːt/), and *nil*.
[src:ascii/0-number] In contexts where at least one adjacent digit distinguishes it from the letter O, the number is sometimes pronounced as *oh* or *o* (/oʊ/).
[src:ascii/0-number] Informal or slang terms for 0 include *zilch* and *zip*.
[src:ascii/0-number] Historically, *ought*, *aught* (/ɔːt/), and *cipher* have also been used.
[src:ascii/0-number] The word *zero* came into the English language via French *zéro* from the Italian *zero*, a contraction of the Venetian *zevero* form of Italian *zefiro*, itself borrowed from Arabic *ṣafira* or *ṣifr*.
[src:ascii/0-number] In pre-Islamic time the word *ṣifr* (Arabic صفر) had the meaning "empty".
[src:ascii/0-number] *Sifr* evolved to mean zero when it was used to translate *śūnya* (Sanskrit: शून्य) from India.
[src:ascii/0-number] The earliest known use of *zero* as a loanword in English literature was 1598.
[src:ascii/0-number] 1250), who grew up in North Africa and is credited with introducing the decimal system to Europe, used the term *zephyrum*.
[src:ascii/0-number] This became *zefiro* in Italian, and was then contracted to *zero* via the Venetian form *zevero*.
[src:ascii/0-number] The Italian word *zefiro* was already in existence (meaning "west wind" from Latin and Greek *Zephyrus*) and may have influenced the spelling when transcribing Arabic *ṣifr*.
[src:ascii/0-number] Depending on the context, there may be different words used for the number zero, or the concept of zero.
[src:ascii/0-number] For the simple notion of lacking, the words "nothing" (although this is not accurate) and "none" are often used.
[src:ascii/0-number] The English words "nought" or "naught", "nil", and null are also synonymous.
[src:ascii/0-number] It is often called "oh" in the context of reading out a string of digits, such as telephone numbers, street addresses, credit card numbers, military time, or years.
[src:ascii/0-number] For example, the area code 201 may be pronounced "two oh one", and the year 1907 is often pronounced "nineteen oh seven".
[src:ascii/0-number] The presence of other digits, indicating that the string contains only numbers, avoids confusion with the letter O.
[src:ascii/0-number] For this reason, systems that include strings with both letters and numbers (such as postcodes in the UK) may exclude the use of the letter O.
[src:ascii/0-number] Slang words for zero include "zip", "zilch", "nada", and "scratch".
[src:ascii/0-number] In the context of sports, "nil" is sometimes used, especially in British English.
[src:ascii/0-number] Several sports have specific words for a score of zero, such as "love" in tennis – possibly from French *l'œuf*, "the egg" – and "duck" in cricket, a shortening of "duck's egg".
[src:ascii/0-number] "Goose egg" is another general slang term used for zero.
[src:ascii/0-number] The concept of zero plays multiple roles in mathematics: as a digit, it is an important part of positional notation for representing numbers, while it also plays an important role as a number in its own right in many algebraic settings.
[src:ascii/0-number] In positional number systems (such as the usual decimal notation for representing numbers), the digit 0 plays the role of a placeholder, indicating that certain powers of the base do not contribute.
[src:ascii/0-number] For example, the decimal number 205 is the sum of two hundreds and five ones, with the 0 digit indicating that no tens are added.
[src:ascii/0-number] The digit plays the same role in decimal fractions and in the decimal representation of other real numbers (indicating whether any tenths, hundredths, thousandths, etc., are present) and in bases other than 10 (for example, in binary, where it indicates which powers of 2 are omitted).
[src:ascii/0-number] The number 0 is the smallest nonnegative integer, and the largest nonpositive integer.
[src:ascii/0-number] The natural number following 0 is 1 and no natural number precedes 0.
[src:ascii/0-number] The number 0 may or may not be considered a natural number, but it is an integer, and hence a rational number and a real number.
[src:ascii/0-number] Zero is even (that is, a multiple of 2), and is also an integer multiple of any other integer.
[src:ascii/0-number] It is neither a prime number nor a composite number.
[src:ascii/0-number] The number 0 is regarded as neither positive nor negative, and is usually displayed as the origin of a number line.
[src:ascii/0-number] When the real numbers are extended to form the complex numbers, 0 becomes the origin of the complex plane.
[src:ascii/0-number] The following are some basic rules for dealing with the number 0.
[src:ascii/0-number] These rules apply for any real or complex number *x*, unless otherwise stated.
[src:ascii/0-number] The expression ⁠0/0⁠, which may be obtained in an attempt to determine the limit of an expression of the form ⁠*f*(*x*)/*g*(*x*)⁠ as a result of applying the lim operator independently to both operands of the fraction, is a so-called "indeterminate form".
[src:ascii/0-number] That does not mean that the limit sought is necessarily undefined; rather, it means that the limit of ⁠*f*(*x*)/*g*(*x*)⁠, if it exists, must be found by another method, such as l'Hôpital's rule.
[src:ascii/0-number] The sum of 0 numbers (the *empty sum*) is 0, and the product of 0 numbers (the *empty product*) is 1.
[src:ascii/0-number] The factorial 0! evaluates to 1, as a special case of the empty product.
[src:ascii/0-number] The role of 0 as the smallest counting number can be generalized or extended in various ways.
[src:ascii/0-number] In set theory, 0 is the cardinality of the empty set (notated as "{ }", " ${\textstyle \emptyset }$ ", or "∅"): if one does not have any apples, then one has 0 apples.
[src:ascii/0-number] In fact, in certain axiomatic developments of mathematics from set theory, 0 is *defined* to be the empty set.
[src:ascii/0-number] When this is done, the empty set is the von Neumann cardinal assignment for a set with no elements, which is the empty set.
[src:ascii/0-number] Also in set theory, 0 is the lowest ordinal number, corresponding to the empty set viewed as a well-ordered set.
[src:ascii/0-number] In order theory (and especially its subfield lattice theory), 0 may denote the least element of a lattice or other partially ordered set.
[src:ascii/0-number] The role of 0 as additive identity generalizes beyond elementary algebra.
[src:ascii/0-number] In abstract algebra, 0 is commonly used to denote a zero element, which is the identity element for addition (if defined on the structure under consideration) and an absorbing element for multiplication (if defined).
[src:ascii/0-number] Examples include identity elements of additive groups and vector spaces.
[src:ascii/0-number] Another example is the **zero function** (or **zero map**) on a domain D.
[src:ascii/0-number] This is the constant function with 0 as its only possible output value, that is, it is the function f defined by *f*(*x*) = 0 for all x in D.
[src:ascii/0-number] As a function from the real numbers to the real numbers, the zero function is the only function that is both even and odd.
[src:ascii/0-number] Ancient Egyptian numerals were of base 10.
[src:ascii/0-number] They used hieroglyphs for the digits and were not positional.
[src:ascii/0-number] In one papyrus written around 1770 BC, a scribe recorded daily incomes and expenditures for the pharaoh's court, using the *nfr* hieroglyph to indicate cases where the amount of a foodstuff received was exactly equal to the amount disbursed.
[src:ascii/0-number] Egyptologist Alan Gardiner suggested that the *nfr* hieroglyph was being used as a symbol for zero.
[src:ascii/0-number] The same symbol was also used to indicate the base level in drawings of tombs and pyramids, and distances were measured relative to the base line as being above or below this line.
[src:ascii/0-number] By the middle of the 2nd millennium BC, Babylonian mathematics had a sophisticated base 60 positional numeral system, but a positional value of zero was indicated by a *space* between numerals.
[src:ascii/0-number] In a tablet unearthed at Kish (dating to as early as 700 BC), the scribe Bêl-bân-aplu used three hooks as a placeholder.
[src:ascii/0-number] By 300 BC, a punctuation symbol (two slanted wedges) was repurposed as a placeholder.
[src:ascii/0-number] The Mesoamerican Long Count calendar developed in south-central Mexico and Central America required the use of zero as a placeholder within its vigesimal (base-20) positional numeral system.
[src:ascii/0-number] Many different glyphs, including the partial quatrefoil were used as a zero symbol for these Long Count dates, the earliest of which (on Stela 2 at Chiapa de Corzo, Chiapas) has a date of 36 BC.
[src:ascii/0-number] Since the eight earliest Long Count dates appear outside the Maya homeland, it is generally believed that the use of zero in the Americas predated the Maya and was possibly the invention of the Olmecs.
[src:ascii/0-number] Many of the earliest Long Count dates were found within the Olmec heartland, although the Olmec civilization ended by the 4th century BC, several centuries before the earliest known Long Count dates.
[src:ascii/0-number] Although zero became an integral part of Maya numerals, with a different, empty tortoise-like "shell shape" used for many depictions of the "zero" numeral, it is assumed not to have influenced Old World numeral systems.
[src:ascii/0-number] Quipu, a knotted cord device, used in the Inca Empire and its predecessor societies in the Andean region to record accounting and other digital data, is encoded in a base ten positional system.
[src:ascii/0-number] Zero is represented by the absence of a knot in the appropriate position.
[src:ascii/0-number] The earliest confidently cited exemplar of the Greek use of the Hellenistic zero appears in Hipparchus in 140 CE.
[src:ascii/0-number] The archaic Greece had no symbol for zero (μηδέν, pronounced *mēdén*), and did not use a digit placeholder for it.
[src:ascii/0-number] According to mathematician Charles Seife, after the Babylonian placeholder zero shows up sometime shortly after 500 BC, Greek astronomers began to use the lowercase Greek letter *ό* (*όμικρον*: omicron) as a placeholder or representation of ground-level/null degree value.
[src:ascii/0-number] However, after using the Babylonian placeholder zero for astronomical calculations they would typically convert the numbers back into Greek numerals.
[src:ascii/0-number] As with the rejection of infinitesimals by Pythagoras, Greeks appear to maintain to a philosophical opposition to using zero as a number.
[src:ascii/0-number] "The whole of the Greek universe rested on this pillar: There is no void." Nieder dates the appearance of zero in Greek astronomical texts after 400 BC and mathematician Robert Kaplan further specifies that it must have been after the conquests of Alexander.
[src:ascii/0-number] Greeks seemed unsure about the status of zero as a number.
[src:ascii/0-number] Some of them asked themselves, "How can not being be?", leading to philosophical and, by the medieval period, religious arguments about the nature and existence of zero and the vacuum.
[src:ascii/0-number] The paradoxes of Zeno of Elea depend in large part on the uncertain interpretation of zero.
[src:ascii/0-number] By AD 150, Ptolemy, influenced by Hipparchus and the Babylonians, was using a symbol for zero (—°) in his work on mathematical astronomy called the *Syntaxis Mathematica*, also known as the *Almagest*.
[src:ascii/0-number] This Hellenistic zero was perhaps the earliest documented use of a numeral representing zero in the Old World.
[src:ascii/0-number] Ptolemy used it many times in his *Almagest* (VI.8) for the magnitude of solar and lunar eclipses.
[src:ascii/0-number] It represented the value of both digits and minutes of immersion at first and last contact.
[src:ascii/0-number] Digits varied continuously from 0 to 12 to 0 as the Moon passed over the Sun (a triangular pulse), where twelve digits was the angular diameter of the Sun.
[src:ascii/0-number] Minutes of immersion was tabulated from 0′0″ to 31′20″ to 0′0″, where 0′0″ used the symbol as a placeholder in two positions of his sexagesimal positional numeral system, while the combination meant a zero angle.
[src:ascii/0-number] Minutes of immersion was also a continuous function ⁠1/12⁠ 31′20″ √d(24−d) (a triangular pulse with convex sides), where d was the digit function and 31′20″ was the sum of the radii of the Sun's and Moon's discs.
[src:ascii/0-number] Ptolemy's symbol was a placeholder as well as a number used by two continuous mathematical functions, one within another, so it meant zero, not none.
[src:ascii/0-number] Over time, Ptolemy's zero tended to increase in size and lose the overline, sometimes depicted as a large elongated 0-like omicron "Ο" or as omicron with overline "ō" instead of a dot with overline.
[src:ascii/0-number] This use was repeated in 525 in an equivalent table, that was translated via the Latin *nulla* ("none") by Dionysius Exiguus, alongside Roman numerals.
[src:ascii/0-number] When division produced zero as a remainder, *nihil*, meaning "nothing", was used.
[src:ascii/0-number] These medieval zeros were used by all future medieval calculators of Easter.
[src:ascii/0-number] The initial "N" was used as a zero symbol in a table of Roman numerals by Bede—or his colleagues—around AD 725.
[src:ascii/0-number] The *Sūnzĭ Suànjīng*, of unknown date but estimated to be dated from the 1st to 5th centuries AD, describe how the 4th century BC Chinese counting rods system enabled one to perform positional decimal calculations.
[src:ascii/0-number] As noted in the *Xiahou Yang Suanjing* (425–468 AD), to multiply or divide a number by 10, 100, 1000, or 10000, all one needs to do, with rods on the counting board, is to move them forwards, or back, by 1, 2, 3, or 4 places.
[src:ascii/0-number] The rods gave the decimal representation of a number, with an empty space denoting zero.
[src:ascii/0-number] A circa 190 AD, manual, the "Supplementary Notes on the Art of Figures", by Xu Yue, also outlines the techniques to add, subtract, multiply, and divide numbers, containing zero values in a decimal power, on *counting devices*, that include counting rods, and abacus.
[src:ascii/0-number] Chinese authors had been familiar with the idea of negative numbers, and decimal fractions, by the Han dynasty (2nd century AD), as seen in *The Nine Chapters on the Mathematical Art*.
[src:ascii/0-number] Qín Jiǔsháo's 1247 *Mathematical Treatise in Nine Sections* is the oldest surviving Chinese mathematical text using a round symbol '〇' for zero.
[src:ascii/0-number] The origin of this symbol is unknown; it may have been produced by modifying a square symbol.
[src:ascii/0-number] Zero was not treated as a number at that time, but as a "vacant position".
[src:ascii/0-number] A variety of Chinese characters have been used, through history, to represent zero: 空, 零, 洞, 〇.
[src:ascii/0-number] 3rd or 2nd century BC), a Sanskrit prosody scholar, used binary sequences, in the form of short and long syllables (the latter equal in length to two short syllables), to identify the possible valid Sanskrit meters, a notation similar to Morse code.
[src:ascii/0-number] Pingala used the Sanskrit word *śūnya* explicitly to refer to zero.
[src:ascii/0-number] A decimal place value grapheme for zero was developed in India.
[src:ascii/0-number] The *Lokavibhāga*, a Jain text on cosmology surviving in a medieval Sanskrit translation of the Prakrit original, which is internally dated to AD 458 (Saka era 380), uses a decimal place-value system, including a zero.
[src:ascii/0-number] In this text, *śūnya* ("void, empty") is also used to refer to zero.
[src:ascii/0-number] 499), states *sthānāt sthānaṁ daśaguṇaṁ syāt* "from place to place each is ten times the preceding".
[src:ascii/0-number] The oldest, firmly dated use of zero as a decimal figure, found on the Sambor Inscription.
[src:ascii/0-number] There are numerous copper plate inscriptions with the same small o in them, some of them possibly dated to the 6th century, but their date or authenticity may be open to doubt.
[src:ascii/0-number] A stone tablet found in the ruins of a temple near Sambor on the Mekong, Kratié Province, Cambodia, includes the inscription of "605" in Khmer numerals (a set of numeral glyphs for the Hindu–Arabic numeral system).
[src:ascii/0-number] The number is the year of the inscription in the Saka era, corresponding to a date of AD 683.
[src:ascii/0-number] The first known use of special glyphs for the decimal digits that includes the indubitable appearance of a symbol for the digit zero, a small circle, appears on a stone inscription found at the Chaturbhuj Temple, Gwalior, in India, dated AD 876.
[src:ascii/0-number] A symbol for zero, a black dot, is used throughout the Bakhshali manuscript, a practical manual on arithmetic for merchants.
[src:ascii/0-number] The Bodleian Library reported radiocarbon dating results for six folio from the manuscript, indicating that they came from different centuries, but date the manuscript to AD 799 – 1102.
[src:ascii/0-number] The Arabic-language inheritance of science was largely Greek, followed by Hindu influences.
[src:ascii/0-number] In 773, at Al-Mansur's behest, translations were made of many ancient treatises including Greek, Roman, Indian, and others.
[src:ascii/0-number] In AD 813, astronomical tables were prepared by a Persian mathematician, Muḥammad ibn Mūsā al-Khwārizmī, using Hindu numerals; and about 825, he published a book synthesizing Greek and Hindu knowledge and also contained his own contribution to mathematics including an explanation of the use of zero.
[src:ascii/0-number] This book was later translated into Latin in the 12th century under the title *Algoritmi de numero Indorum*.
[src:ascii/0-number] This title means "al-Khwarizmi on the Numerals of the Indians".
[src:ascii/0-number] The word "Algoritmi" was the translator's Latinization of Al-Khwarizmi's name, and the word "Algorithm" or "Algorism" started to acquire a meaning of any arithmetic based on decimals.
[src:ascii/0-number] Muhammad ibn Ahmad al-Khwarizmi, in 976, stated that if no number appears in the place of tens in a calculation, a little circle should be used "to keep the rows".
[src:ascii/0-number] The Hindu–Arabic numeral system (base 10) reached Western Europe in the 11th century, via Al-Andalus, through Spanish Muslims, the Moors, together with knowledge of classical astronomy and instruments like the astrolabe.
[src:ascii/0-number] Gerbert of Aurillac is credited with reintroducing the lost teachings into Catholic Europe.
[src:ascii/0-number] For this reason, the numerals came to be known in Europe as "Arabic numerals".
[src:ascii/0-number] From the 13th century, manuals on calculation (adding, multiplying, extracting roots, etc.) became common in Europe where they were called *algorismus* after the Persian mathematician al-Khwārizmī.
[src:ascii/0-number] One popular manual was written by Johannes de Sacrobosco in the early 1200s and was one of the earliest scientific books to be printed, in 1488.
[src:ascii/0-number] The practice of calculating on paper using Hindu–Arabic numerals only gradually displaced calculation by abacus and recording with Roman numerals.
[src:ascii/0-number] In the 16th century, Hindu–Arabic numerals became the predominant numerals used in Europe.
[src:ascii/0-number] Today, the numerical digit 0 is usually written as a circle or ellipse.
[src:ascii/0-number] Traditionally, many print typefaces made the capital letter O more rounded than the narrower, elliptical digit 0.
[src:ascii/0-number] Typewriters originally made no distinction in shape between O and 0; some models did not even have a separate key for the digit 0.
[src:ascii/0-number] The distinction came into prominence on modern character displays.
[src:ascii/0-number] A slashed zero ( $0\!\!\!{/}$ ) is often used to distinguish the number from the letter (mostly in computing, navigation and in the military, for example).
[src:ascii/0-number] The digit 0 with a dot in the center seems to have originated as an option on IBM 3270 displays and has continued with some modern computer typefaces such as Andalé Mono, and in some airline reservation systems.
[src:ascii/0-number] One variation uses a short vertical bar instead of the dot.
[src:ascii/0-number] Some fonts designed for use with computers made the "0" character more squared at the edges, like a rectangle, and the "O" character more rounded.
[src:ascii/0-number] A further distinction is made in falsification-hindering typeface as used on German car number plates by slitting open the digit 0 on the upper right side.
[src:ascii/0-number] In some systems either the letter O or the numeral 0, or both, are excluded from use, to avoid confusion.
[src:ascii/0-number] The value zero plays a special role for many physical quantities.
[src:ascii/0-number] For some quantities, the zero level is naturally distinguished from all other levels, whereas for others it is more or less arbitrarily chosen.
[src:ascii/0-number] For example, for an absolute temperature (typically measured in kelvins), zero is the lowest possible value.
[src:ascii/0-number] (Negative temperatures can be defined for some physical systems, but negative-temperature systems are not actually colder.) This is in contrast to temperatures on the Celsius scale, for example, where zero is arbitrarily defined to be at the freezing point of water.
[src:ascii/0-number] Measuring sound intensity in decibels or phons, the zero level is arbitrarily set at a reference value—for example, at a value for the threshold of hearing.
[src:ascii/0-number] Modern computers store information in binary, that is, using an "alphabet" that contains only two symbols, usually chosen to be "0" and "1".
[src:ascii/0-number] Binary coding is convenient for digital electronics, where "0" and "1" can stand for the absence or presence of electrical current in a wire.
[src:ascii/0-number] Computer programmers typically use high-level programming languages that are more intelligible to humans than the binary instructions that are directly executed by the central processing unit.
[src:ascii/0-number] 0 plays various important roles in high-level languages.
[src:ascii/0-number] The most common practice throughout human history has been to start counting at one, and this is the practice in early classic programming languages such as Fortran and COBOL.
[src:ascii/0-number] For example, the elements of an array are numbered starting from 0 in C, so that for an array of *n* items the sequence of array indices runs from 0 to *n*−1.
[src:ascii/0-number] Since C arrays are accessed by the array's first element memory address plus an offset, the initial pointer plus with offset zero refers to the first element of the array.
[src:ascii/0-number] There can be confusion between 0- and 1-based indexing; for example, Java's JDBC indexes parameters from 1 although Java itself uses 0-based indexing.
[src:ascii/0-number] In C, a byte containing the value 0 serves to indicate where a string of characters ends.
[src:ascii/0-number] Also, 0 is a standard way to refer to a null pointer in code.
[src:ascii/0-number] In databases, it is possible for a field not to have a value.
[src:ascii/0-number] For numeric fields it is not the value zero.
[src:ascii/0-number] For text fields this is not blank nor the empty string.
[src:ascii/0-number] The presence of null values leads to three-valued logic.
[src:ascii/0-number] No longer is a condition either *true* or *false*, but it can be *undetermined*.
[src:ascii/0-number] Any computation including a null value delivers a null result.
[src:ascii/0-number] In mathematics, there is no "positive zero" or "negative zero" distinct from zero; both −0 and +0 represent exactly the same number.
[src:ascii/0-number] However, in some computer hardware signed number representations, zero has two distinct representations, a positive one grouped with the positive numbers and a negative one grouped with the negatives.
[src:ascii/0-number] This kind of dual representation is known as signed zero, with the latter form sometimes called negative zero.
[src:ascii/0-number] These representations include the signed magnitude and ones' complement binary integer representations (but not the two's complement binary form used in most modern computers), and most floating-point number representations (such as IEEE 754 and IBM S/360 floating-point formats).
[src:ascii/0-number] An epoch, in computing terminology, is the date and time associated with a zero timestamp.
[src:ascii/0-number] The Unix epoch begins the midnight before the first of January 1970.
[src:ascii/0-number] The Classic Mac OS epoch and Palm OS epoch begin the midnight before the first of January 1904.
[src:ascii/0-number] Many APIs and operating systems that require applications to return an integer value as an exit status typically use zero to indicate success and non-zero values to indicate specific error or warning conditions.
[src:ascii/0-number] Programmers often use a slashed zero to avoid confusion with the letter "O".
[src:ascii/0-number] In comparative zoology and cognitive science, recognition that some animals display awareness of the concept of zero leads to the conclusion that the capability for numerical abstraction arose early in the evolution of species.
[src:ascii/0-number] In the BC calendar era, the year 1 BC is the first year before AD 1; there is not a year zero.
[src:ascii/0-number] By contrast, in astronomical year numbering, the year 1 BC is numbered 0, the year 2 BC is numbered −1, and so forth.
[src:ascii/1] In mathematics, 1 is the multiplicative identity, meaning that any number multiplied by 1 equals the same number.
[src:ascii/1] 1 is by convention not considered a prime number.
[src:ascii/1] In digital technology, 1 represents the "on" state in binary code, the foundation of computing.
[src:ascii/1] Philosophically, 1 symbolizes the ultimate reality or source of existence in various traditions.
[src:ascii/1] The number 1 is the first natural number after 0.
[src:ascii/1] Each natural number, including 1, is constructed by succession, that is, by adding 1 to the previous natural number.
[src:ascii/1] Although 1 meets the naïve definition of a prime number, being evenly divisible only by 1 and itself (also 1), by modern convention it is regarded as neither a prime nor a composite number.
[src:ascii/1] The number 1 is the multiplicative identity of the integers, real numbers, and complex numbers, that is, any number n multiplied by 1 remains unchanged $1\times n=n\times 1=n$ .
[src:ascii/1] As a result, the square $1^{2}=1$ , square root ${\sqrt {1}}=1$ , and any other power of 1 is always equal to 1 itself.
[src:ascii/1] More generally, in algebra, it denotes the multiplicative identity in any unital ring or field.
[src:ascii/1] An element with a multiplicative inverse is called a unit, generalizing the role of 1.
[src:ascii/1] For any number a , the first power satisfies $a^{1}=a$ , so that 1 is also the identity for any power semigroup.
[src:ascii/1] Moreover, the empty product, that is the product of a set of zero numbers, is also 1.
[src:ascii/1] Thus any number raised to the zero power is one, and 0! is 1.
[src:ascii/1] Different mathematical constructions of the natural numbers represent 1 in various ways.
[src:ascii/1] In Giuseppe Peano's original formulation of the Peano axioms, a set of postulates to define the natural numbers in a precise and logical way, 1 was treated as the starting point of the sequence of natural numbers.
[src:ascii/1] Peano later revised his axioms to begin the sequence with 0.
[src:ascii/1] In the Von Neumann cardinal assignment of natural numbers, where each number is defined as a set that contains all numbers before it, 1 is represented as the singleton $\{0\}$ , a set containing only the element 0.
[src:ascii/1] The unary numeral system, as used in tallying, is an example of a "base-1" number system, since only one mark – the tally itself – is needed.
[src:ascii/1] While this is the simplest way to represent the natural numbers, base-1 is rarely used as a practical base for counting due to its difficult readability.
[src:ascii/1] In many mathematical and engineering problems, numeric values are typically normalized to fall within the unit interval $[0,1]$ , where 1 represents the maximum possible value.
[src:ascii/1] For example, by definition 1 is the probability of an event that is absolutely or almost certain to occur.
[src:ascii/1] Likewise, vectors are often normalized into unit vectors (i.e., vectors of magnitude one), because these often have more desirable properties.
[src:ascii/1] Functions are often normalized by the condition that they have integral one, maximum value one, or square integral one, depending on the application.
[src:ascii/1] 1 is the most common leading digit in many sets of real-world numerical data.
[src:ascii/1] This is a consequence of Benford’s law, which states that the probability for a specific leading digit d is ${\textstyle \log _{10}\left({\frac {d+1}{d}}\right)}$ .
[src:ascii/1] The tendency for real-world numbers to grow exponentially or logarithmically biases the distribution towards smaller leading digits, with 1 occurring approximately 30% of the time.
[src:ascii/1] 1 is the value of Legendre's constant, introduced in 1808 by Adrien-Marie Legendre to express the asymptotic behavior of the prime-counting function.
[src:ascii/1] The Weil's conjecture on Tamagawa numbers states that the Tamagawa number $\tau (G)$ , a geometrical measure of a connected linear algebraic group over a global number field, is 1 for all simply connected groups (those that are path-connected with no 'holes').
[src:ascii/1] Words that derive their meaning from *one* include *alone*, which signifies *all one* in the sense of being by oneself, *none* meaning *not one*, *once* denoting *one time*, and *atone* meaning to become *at one* with the someone.
[src:ascii/1] Combining *alone* with *only* (implying *one-like*) leads to *lonely*, conveying a sense of solitude.
[src:ascii/1] Other common numeral prefixes for the number 1 include *uni-* (e.g., unicycle, universe, unicorn), *sol-* (e.g., solo dance), derived from Latin, or *mono-* (e.g., monorail, monogamy, monopoly) derived from Greek.
[src:ascii/1] Among the earliest known records of a numeral system, is the Sumerian decimal-sexagesimal system on clay tablets dating from the first half of the third millennium BCE.
[src:ascii/1] Archaic Sumerian numerals for 1 and 60 both consisted of horizontal semi-circular symbols, by c.
[src:ascii/1] 2350 BCE, the older Sumerian curviform numerals were replaced with cuneiform symbols, with 1 and 60 both represented by the same mostly vertical symbol.
[src:ascii/1] The Sumerian cuneiform system is a direct ancestor to the Eblaite and Assyro-Babylonian Semitic cuneiform decimal systems.
[src:ascii/1] Surviving Babylonian documents date mostly from Old Babylonian (c.
[src:ascii/1] The Babylonian cuneiform script notation for numbers used the same symbol for 1 and 60 as in the Sumerian system.
[src:ascii/1] The most common representative glyph used in the modern Western world for the number 1 is the Arabic numeral, a vertical line, often with a serif at the top and sometimes a short horizontal line at the bottom.
[src:ascii/1] It can be traced back to the Brahmic script of ancient India, as represented by Ashoka as a simple vertical line in his Edicts of Ashoka in c.
[src:ascii/1] This script's numeral shapes were transmitted to Europe via the Maghreb and Al-Andalus during the Middle Ages The Arabic numerals, and other glyphs used to represent the number one (e.g., Roman numeral (I ), Chinese numeral (一)) are logograms.
[src:ascii/1] These symbols directly represent the concept of 'one' without breaking it down into phonetic components.
[src:ascii/1] This Woodstock typewriter from the 1940s lacks a separate key for the numeral 1.
[src:ascii/1] and represents the numeral 1 as similar to a small-caps I.
[src:ascii/1] In modern typefaces, the shape of the character for the digit 1 is typically typeset as a *lining figure* with an ascender, such that the digit is the same height and width as a capital letter.
[src:ascii/1] In many typefaces with text figures, the numeral 1 features parallel serifs at the top and bottom, resembling a small caps version of the Roman numeral I.
[src:ascii/1] Many older typewriters do not have a dedicated key for the numeral 1, requiring the use of the lowercase letter *L* or uppercase *I* as substitutes.
[src:ascii/1] The lower case "j" can be considered a swash variant of a lower-case Roman numeral "i", often employed for the final i of a "lower-case" Roman numeral.
[src:ascii/1] It is also possible to find historic examples of the use of *j* or *J* as a substitute for the Arabic numeral 1.
[src:ascii/1] In German, the serif at the top may be extended into a long upstroke as long as the vertical line.
[src:ascii/1] This variation can lead to confusion with the glyph used for seven in other countries and so to provide a visual distinction between the two the digit 7 may be written with a horizontal stroke through the vertical line.
[src:ascii/1] In digital technology, data is represented by binary code, i.e., a base-2 numeral system with numbers represented by a sequence of 1s and 0s.
[src:ascii/1] Digitised data is represented in physical devices, such as computers, as pulses of electricity through switching devices such as transistors or logic gates where "1" represents the value for "on".
[src:ascii/1] As such, the numerical value of true is equal to 1 in many programming languages.
[src:ascii/1] In lambda calculus and computability theory, natural numbers are represented by Church encoding as functions, where the Church numeral for 1 is represented by the function f applied to an argument x once (1 $fx=fx$ ).
[src:ascii/1] In physics, selected physical constants are set to 1 in natural unit systems in order to simplify the form of equations; for example, in Planck units the speed of light equals 1.
[src:ascii/1] Dimensionless quantities are also known as 'quantities of dimension one'.
[src:ascii/1] In quantum mechanics, the normalization condition for wavefunctions requires the integral of a wavefunction's squared modulus to be equal to 1.
[src:ascii/1] In chemistry, hydrogen, the first element of the periodic table and the most abundant element in the known universe, has an atomic number of 1.
[src:ascii/1] Group 1 of the periodic table consists of hydrogen and the alkali metals.
[src:ascii/1] In philosophy, the number 1 is commonly regarded as a symbol of unity, often representing God or the universe in monotheistic traditions.
[src:ascii/1] The Pythagoreans considered the numbers to be plural and therefore did not classify 1 itself as a number, but as the origin of all numbers.
[src:ascii/1] In their number philosophy, where odd numbers were considered male and even numbers female, 1 was considered neutral capable of transforming even numbers to odd and vice versa by addition.
[src:ascii/1] The Neopythagorean philosopher Nicomachus of Gerasa's number treatise, as recovered by Boethius in the Latin translation *Introduction to Arithmetic*, affirmed that one is not a number, but the source of number.
[src:ascii/1] In the philosophy of Plotinus (and that of other neoplatonists), 'The One' is the ultimate reality and source of all existence.
[src:ascii/1] Philo of Alexandria (20 BC – AD 50) regarded the number one as God's number, and the basis for all numbers.
[src:ascii/12-bit-computing] In computer architecture, **12-bit** integers, memory addresses, or other data units are those that are 12 bits (1.5 octets) wide.
[src:ascii/12-bit-computing] Also, 12-bit central processing unit (CPU) and arithmetic logic unit (ALU) architectures are those that are based on registers, address buses, or data buses of that size.
[src:ascii/12-bit-computing] Before the widespread adoption of ASCII in the late 1960s, six-bit character codes were common and a 12-bit word, which could hold two characters, was a convenient size.
[src:ascii/12-bit-computing] This also made it useful for storing a single decimal digit along with a sign.
[src:ascii/12-bit-computing] Possibly the best-known 12-bit CPUs are the PDP-8 and its descendants (such as the Intersil 6100 microprocessor), which were produced in various forms from August 1963 to mid-1990.
[src:ascii/12-bit-computing] Many analog to digital converters (ADCs) have a 12-bit resolution.
[src:ascii/12-bit-computing] Some PIC microcontrollers use a 12-bit instruction word but handle only 8-bit data.
[src:ascii/12-bit-computing] 12 binary digits, or 3 nibbles (a 'tribble'), have 4096 (10000 octal, 1000 hexadecimal) distinct combinations.
[src:ascii/12-bit-computing] Hence, a microprocessor with 12-bit memory addresses can directly access 4096 words (4 kW) of word-addressable memory.
[src:ascii/12-bit-computing] IBM System/360 instruction formats use a 12-bit displacement field which, added to the contents of a base register, can address 4096 bytes of memory in a region that begins at the address in the base register.
[src:ascii/16-bit-computing] In computer architecture, **16-bit** integers, memory addresses, or other data units are those that are 16 bits (2 octets) wide.
[src:ascii/16-bit-computing] Also, 16-bit central processing unit (CPU) and arithmetic logic unit (ALU) architectures are those that are based on registers, address buses, or data buses of that size.
[src:ascii/16-bit-computing] 16-bit microcomputers are microcomputers that use 16-bit microprocessors.
[src:ascii/16-bit-computing] A 16-bit register can store 216 different values.
[src:ascii/16-bit-computing] The range of integer values that can be stored in 16 bits depends on the integer representation used.
[src:ascii/16-bit-computing] With the two most common representations, the range is 0 through 65,535 (216 − 1) for representation as an (unsigned) binary number, and −32,768 (−1 × 215) through 32,767 (215 − 1) for representation as two's complement.
[src:ascii/16-bit-computing] Since 216 is 65,536, a processor with 16-bit memory addresses can directly access 64 KiB (65,536 bytes) of byte-addressable memory.
[src:ascii/16-bit-computing] If a system uses segmentation with 16-bit segment offsets, more can be accessed.
[src:ascii/16-bit-computing] 1951) was quite possibly the first-ever 16-bit computer.
[src:ascii/16-bit-computing] It had an unusual word size for the era; most systems used six-bit character code and used a word length of some multiple of 6-bits.
[src:ascii/16-bit-computing] This changed with the effort to introduce ASCII, which used a 7-bit code and naturally led to the use of an 8-bit multiple which could store a single ASCII character or two binary-coded decimal digits.
[src:ascii/16-bit-computing] The 16-bit word length thus became more common in the 1960s, especially on minicomputer systems.
[src:ascii/16-bit-computing] 1965–70) include the IBM 1130, the HP 2100, the Data General Nova, and the DEC PDP-11.
[src:ascii/16-bit-computing] Early 16-bit microprocessors, often modeled on one of the mini platforms, began to appear in the 1970s.
[src:ascii/16-bit-computing] Early single-chip 16-bit microprocessors (c.
[src:ascii/16-bit-computing] Other notable 16-bit processors include the Intel 8086, the Intel 80286, the WDC 65C816, and the Zilog Z8000.
[src:ascii/16-bit-computing] The Intel 8088 was binary compatible with the Intel 8086, and was 16-bit in that its registers were 16 bits wide, and arithmetic instructions could operate on 16-bit quantities, even though its external bus was 8 bits wide.
[src:ascii/16-bit-computing] 16-bit processors have been almost entirely supplanted in the personal computer industry, and are used less than 32-bit (or 8-bit) CPUs in embedded applications.
[src:ascii/16-bit-computing] The Motorola 68000 is sometimes called 16-bit because of the way it handles basic arithmetic.
[src:ascii/16-bit-computing] The instruction set was based on 32-bit numbers and the internal registers were 32 bits wide, so by common definitions, the 68000 is a 32-bit design.
[src:ascii/16-bit-computing] Internally, 32-bit arithmetic is performed using two 16-bit operations, and this leads to some descriptions of the system as 16-bit, or "16/32".
[src:ascii/16-bit-computing] Such solutions have a long history in the computer field, with various designs performing math even one bit at a time, known as "serial arithmetic", while most designs by the 1970s processed at least a few bits at a time.
[src:ascii/16-bit-computing] A common example is the Data General Nova, which was a 16-bit design that performed 16-bit math as a series of four 4-bit operations.
[src:ascii/16-bit-computing] 4-bits was the word size of a widely available single-chip ALU and thus allowed for inexpensive implementation.
[src:ascii/16-bit-computing] Using the definition being applied to the 68000, the Nova would be a 4-bit computer, or 4/16.
[src:ascii/16-bit-computing] Not long after the introduction of the Nova, a second version was introduced, the SuperNova, which included four of the 4-bit ALUs running in parallel to perform math 16 bits at a time and therefore offer higher performance.
[src:ascii/16-bit-computing] This was invisible to the user and the programs, which always used 16-bit instructions and data.
[src:ascii/16-bit-computing] In a similar fashion, later 68000-family members, starting with the Motorola 68020, had 32-bit ALUs.
[src:ascii/16-bit-computing] One may also see references to systems being, or not being, 16-bit based on some other measure.
[src:ascii/16-bit-computing] One common one is when the address space is not the same size of bits as the internal registers.
[src:ascii/16-bit-computing] Most 8-bit CPUs of the 1970s fall into this category; the MOS 6502, Intel 8080, Zilog Z80 and most others had 16-bit address space which provided 64 KiB of address space.
[src:ascii/16-bit-computing] This also meant address manipulation required two instruction cycles.
[src:ascii/16-bit-computing] For this reason, most processors had special 8-bit addressing modes, the zero page, improving speed.
[src:ascii/16-bit-computing] This sort of difference between internal register size and external address size remained in the 1980s, although often reversed, as memory costs of the era made a machine with 32-bit addressing, 2 or 4 GiB, a practical impossibility.
[src:ascii/16-bit-computing] For example, the 68000 exposed only 24 bits of addressing on the DIP, limiting it to a still huge (for the era) 16 MiB.
[src:ascii/16-bit-computing] A similar analysis applies to Intel's 80286 CPU replacement, called the 386SX, which is a 32-bit processor with 32-bit ALU and internal 32-bit data paths with a 16-bit external bus and 24-bit addressing of the processor it replaced.
[src:ascii/16-bit-computing] In the context of IBM PC compatible and Wintel platforms, a 16-bit application is any software written for MS-DOS, OS/2 1.x or early versions of Microsoft Windows which originally ran on the 16-bit Intel 8088 and Intel 80286 microprocessors.
[src:ascii/16-bit-computing] Such applications used a 20-bit or 24-bit segment or selector-offset address representation to extend the range of addressable memory locations beyond what was possible using only 16-bit addresses.
[src:ascii/16-bit-computing] Programs containing more than 216 bytes (65,536 bytes) of instructions and data therefore required special instructions to switch between their 64-kibibyte segments, increasing the complexity of programming 16-bit applications.
[src:ascii/16-bit-computing] Single chip 16-bit microcontrollers appeared around 1983 with the introduction of the Intel 8061.
[src:ascii/16-bit-computing] As of 2025, 16-bit microcontrollers cost well under a US dollar in 100 quantities, similar in price to legacy 8-bit.
[src:ascii/16-bit-computing] Even some 32-bit microcontrollers are priced under a US dollar.
[src:ascii/18-bit-computing] In computer architecture, **18-bit** integers, memory addresses, or other data units are those that are 18 bits (2.25 octets) wide.
[src:ascii/18-bit-computing] Also, 18-bit central processing unit (CPU) and arithmetic logic unit (ALU) architectures are those that are based on registers, address buses, or data buses of that size.
[src:ascii/18-bit-computing] Eighteen binary digits have 262,144 (1000000 octal, 40000 hexadecimal) distinct combinations.
[src:ascii/18-bit-computing] Eighteen bits was a common word size for smaller computers in the 1960s, when large computers often using 36 bit words and 6-bit character sets, sometimes implemented as extensions of BCD, were the norm.
[src:ascii/18-bit-computing] There were also 18-bit teletypes experimented with in the 1940s.
[src:ascii/18-bit-computing] Possibly the most well-known 18-bit computer architectures are the PDP-1, PDP-4, PDP-7, PDP-9 and PDP-15 minicomputers produced by Digital Equipment Corporation from 1960 to 1975.
[src:ascii/18-bit-computing] Digital's PDP-10 used 36-bit words but had 18-bit addresses.
[src:ascii/18-bit-computing] The UNIVAC division of Remington Rand produced several 18-bit computers, including the 1963 UNIVAC 418 and several military systems.
[src:ascii/18-bit-computing] The IBM 7700 Data Acquisition System was announced by IBM on December 2, 1963.
[src:ascii/18-bit-computing] The 1964 CDC 6000 series and successors CDC 7600 and CDC Cyber 70 and 170 series used 60-bit words but had 18-bit addresses.
[src:ascii/18-bit-computing] The BCL Molecular 18 was a group of systems designed and manufactured in the UK in the 1970s and 1980s.
[src:ascii/18-bit-computing] The NASA Standard Spacecraft Computer NSSC-1 was developed as a standard component for the MultiMission Modular Spacecraft at the Goddard Space Flight Center (GSFC) in 1974.
[src:ascii/18-bit-computing] The flying-spot store digital memory in the first experimental electronic switching systems used nine plates of optical memory that were read and written two bits at a time, producing a word size of 18 bits.
[src:ascii/18-bit-computing] Eighteen-bit machines use a variety of character encodings.
[src:ascii/18-bit-computing] The DEC Radix-50, called Radix 508 format, packs three characters plus two bits in each 18-bit word.
[src:ascii/18-bit-computing] The Teletype packs three characters in each 18-bit word; each character a 5-bit Baudot code and an upper-case bit.
[src:ascii/18-bit-computing] The DEC SIXBIT format packs three characters in each 18-bit word, each 6-bit character obtained by stripping the high bits from the 7-bit ASCII code, which folds lowercase to uppercase letters.
[src:ascii/ascii] ASCII encodes each code-point as a value from 0 to 127 – storable as a seven-bit integer.
[src:ascii/ascii] Ninety-five code-points are printable, including digits *0* to *9*, lowercase letters *a* to *z*, uppercase letters *A* to *Z*, and commonly used punctuation symbols.
[src:ascii/ascii] For example, the letter `i` is represented as 105 (decimal).
[src:ascii/ascii] Also, ASCII specifies 33 non-printing control codes which originated with Teletype devices, most of which are now obsolete.
[src:ascii/ascii] The control characters that are still commonly used include carriage return, line feed, and tab.
[src:ascii/ascii] ASCII lacks code-points for characters with diacritical marks and therefore does not directly support terms or names such as résumé, jalapeño, or René.
[src:ascii/ascii] But, depending on hardware and software support, some diacritical marks can be rendered by overwriting a letter with a backtick (`) or tilde (~).
[src:ascii/ascii] The Internet Assigned Numbers Authority (IANA) prefers the name **US-ASCII** for this character encoding.
[src:ascii/ascii] ASCII is the standardisation of a seven-bit teleprinter code developed in part from earlier telegraph codes.
[src:ascii/ascii] Work on the ASCII standard began in May 1961, when IBM engineer Bob Bemer submitted a proposal to the American Standards Association's (ASA) (now the American National Standards Institute or ANSI) X3.2 subcommittee.
[src:ascii/ascii] The first edition of the standard was published in 1963, contemporaneously with the introduction of the Teletype Model 33.
[src:ascii/ascii] It later underwent a major revision in 1967, and several further revisions until 1986.
[src:ascii/ascii] In contrast to earlier telegraph codes such as Baudot, ASCII was ordered for more convenient collation (especially alphabetical sorting of lists), and added controls for devices other than teleprinters.
[src:ascii/ascii] ASCII was developed under the auspices of a committee of the American Standards Association (ASA), called the X3 committee, by its X3.2 (later X3L2) subcommittee, and later by that subcommittee's X3.2.4 working group (now INCITS).
[src:ascii/ascii] The ASA later became the United States of America Standards Institute (USASI) and ultimately became the American National Standards Institute (ANSI).
[src:ascii/ascii] With the other special characters and control codes filled in, ASCII was published as ASA X3.4-1963, leaving 28 code positions without any assigned meaning, reserved for future standardization, and one unassigned control code.
[src:ascii/ascii] There was some debate at the time whether there should be more control characters rather than the lowercase alphabet.
[src:ascii/ascii] The indecision did not last long: during May 1963 the CCITT Working Party on the New Telegraph Alphabet proposed to assign lowercase characters to *sticks* 6 and 7, and International Organization for Standardization TC 97 SC 2 voted during October to incorporate the change into its draft standard.
[src:ascii/ascii] The X3.2.4 task group voted its approval for the change to ASCII at its May 1963 meeting.
[src:ascii/ascii] Locating the lowercase letters in *sticks* 6 and 7 caused the characters to differ in bit pattern from the upper case by a single bit, which simplified case-insensitive character matching and the construction of keyboards and printers.
[src:ascii/ascii] It added the brace and vertical bar characters.
[src:ascii/ascii] It renamed some control characters – SOM became SOH.
[src:ascii/ascii] It moved or removed others – RU was removed.
[src:ascii/ascii] The use of ASCII format for Network Interchange was described in 1969.
[src:ascii/ascii] That document was formally elevated to an Internet Standard in 2015.
[src:ascii/ascii] In the X3.15 standard, the X3 committee also addressed how ASCII should be transmitted (least significant bit first) and recorded on perforated tape.
[src:ascii/ascii] They proposed a 9-track standard for magnetic tape and attempted to deal with some punched card formats.
[src:ascii/ascii] The X3.2 subcommittee designed ASCII based on the earlier teleprinter encoding systems.
[src:ascii/ascii] Like other character encodings, ASCII specifies a correspondence between digital bit patterns and character symbols (i.e. graphemes and control characters).
[src:ascii/ascii] This allows digital devices to communicate with each other and to process, store, and communicate character-oriented information such as written language.
[src:ascii/ascii] Before ASCII was developed, the encodings in use included 26 alphabetic characters, 10 numerical digits, and from 11 to 25 special graphic symbols.
[src:ascii/ascii] To include all these, and control characters compatible with the Comité Consultatif International Téléphonique et Télégraphique (CCITT) International Telegraph Alphabet No.
[src:ascii/ascii] 2 (ITA2) standard of 1932, FIELDATA (1956), and early EBCDIC (1963), more than 64 codes were required for ASCII.
[src:ascii/ascii] ITA2 was in turn based on Baudot code, the 5-bit telegraph code Émile Baudot invented in 1870 and patented in 1874.
[src:ascii/ascii] The committee debated the possibility of a shift function (like in ITA2), which would allow more than 64 codes to be represented by a six-bit code.
[src:ascii/ascii] In a shifted code, some character codes determine choices between options for the following character codes.
[src:ascii/ascii] It allows compact encoding, but is less reliable for data transmission, as an error in transmitting the shift code typically makes a long part of the transmission unreadable.
[src:ascii/ascii] The standards committee decided against shifting, and so ASCII required at least a seven-bit code.
[src:ascii/ascii] The committee considered an eight-bit code, since eight bits (octets) would allow two four-bit patterns to efficiently encode two digits with binary-coded decimal.
[src:ascii/ascii] However, it would require all data transmission to send eight bits when seven could suffice.
[src:ascii/ascii] The committee voted to use a seven-bit code to minimize costs associated with data transmission.
[src:ascii/ascii] Since perforated tape at the time could record eight bits in one position, it also allowed for a parity bit for error checking if desired.
[src:ascii/ascii] Eight-bit machines (with octets as the native data type) that did not use parity checking typically set the eighth bit to 0.
[src:ascii/ascii] The code itself was patterned so that most control codes were together and all graphic codes were together, for ease of identification.
[src:ascii/ascii] The first two so-called *ASCII sticks* (32 positions) were reserved for control characters.
[src:ascii/ascii] The "space" character had to come before graphics to make sorting easier, so it became position 20hex; for the same reason, many special signs commonly used as separators were placed before digits.
[src:ascii/ascii] The committee decided it was important to support uppercase 64-character alphabets, and chose to pattern ASCII so it could be reduced easily to a usable 64-character set of graphic codes, as was done in the DEC SIXBIT code (1963).
[src:ascii/ascii] Lowercase letters were therefore not interleaved with uppercase.
[src:ascii/ascii] To keep options available for lowercase letters and other graphics, the special and numeric codes were arranged before the letters, and the letter *A* was placed in position 41hex to match the draft of the corresponding British standard.
[src:ascii/ascii] The digits 0–9 are prefixed with 011, but the remaining 4 bits correspond to their respective values in binary, making conversion with binary-coded decimal straightforward (for example, 5 is encoded to 011*0101*, where 5 is *0101* in binary).
[src:ascii/ascii] Many of the non-alphanumeric characters were positioned to correspond to their shifted position on typewriters; an important subtlety is that these were based on *mechanical* typewriters, not *electric* typewriters.
[src:ascii/ascii] Mechanical typewriters followed the *de facto* standard set by the Remington No.
[src:ascii/ascii] 2 (1878), the first typewriter with a shift key, and the shifted values of `23456789-` were `"#$%_&'()` – early typewriters omitted *0* and *1*, using *O* (capital letter *o*) and *l* (lowercase letter *L*) instead, but `1!` and `0)` pairs became standard once 0 and 1 became common.
[src:ascii/ascii] Thus, in ASCII `!"#$%` were placed in the second stick, positions 1–5, corresponding to the digits 1–5 in the adjacent stick.
[src:ascii/ascii] The parentheses could not correspond to *9* and *0*, however, because the place corresponding to *0* was taken by the space character.
[src:ascii/ascii] This was accommodated by removing `_` (underscore) from *6* and shifting the remaining characters, which corresponded to many European typewriters that placed the parentheses with *8* and *9*.
[src:ascii/ascii] This discrepancy from typewriters led to bit-paired keyboards, notably the Teletype Model 33, which used the left-shifted layout corresponding to ASCII, differently from traditional mechanical typewriters.
[src:ascii/ascii] 2, and the `,< .>` pairs were used on some keyboards (others, including the No.
[src:ascii/ascii] 2, did not shift `,` (comma) or `.` (full stop) so they could be used in uppercase without unshifting).
[src:ascii/ascii] However, ASCII split the `;:` pair (dating to No.
[src:ascii/ascii] 2), and rearranged mathematical symbols (varied conventions, commonly `-* =+`) to `:* ;+ -=`.
[src:ascii/ascii] Some then-common typewriter characters were not included, notably `½ ¼ ¢`, while ^ ` ~ were included as diacritics for international use, and `< >` for mathematical use, together with the simple line characters `\ |` (in addition to common `/`).
[src:ascii/ascii] The *@* symbol was not used in continental Europe and the committee expected it would be replaced by an accented *À* in the French variation, so the *@* was placed in position 40hex, right before the letter A.
[src:ascii/ascii] The control codes felt essential for data transmission were the start of message (SOM), end of address (EOA), end of message (EOM), end of transmission (EOT), "who are you?" (WRU), "are you?" (RU), a reserved device control (DC0), synchronous idle (SYNC), and acknowledge (ACK).
[src:ascii/ascii] These were positioned to maximize the Hamming distance between their bit patterns.
[src:ascii/ascii] ASCII-code order is also called *ASCIIbetical* order.
[src:ascii/ascii] Collation of data is sometimes done in this order rather than "standard" alphabetical order (collating sequence).
[src:ascii/ascii] An intermediate order converts uppercase letters to lowercase before comparing ASCII values.
[src:ascii/ascii] ASCII reserves the first 32 code points (numbers 0–31 decimal) and the last one (number 127 decimal) for control characters.
[src:ascii/ascii] These are codes intended to control peripheral devices (such as printers), or to provide meta-information about data streams, such as those stored on magnetic tape.
[src:ascii/ascii] Despite their name, these code points do not represent printable characters (i.e. they are not characters at all, but signals).
[src:ascii/ascii] For debugging purposes, "placeholder" symbols (such as those given in ISO 2047 and its predecessors) are assigned to them.
[src:ascii/ascii] For example, character 0x0A represents the "line feed" function (which causes a printer to advance its paper), and character 8 represents "backspace".
[src:ascii/ascii] RFC 2822 refers to control characters that do not include carriage return, line feed or white space as non-whitespace control characters.
[src:ascii/ascii] Except for the control characters that prescribe elementary line-oriented formatting, ASCII does not define any mechanism for describing the structure or appearance of text within a document.
[src:ascii/ascii] Other schemes, such as markup languages, address page and document layout and formatting.
[src:ascii/ascii] The original ASCII standard used only short descriptive phrases for each control character.
[src:ascii/ascii] The ambiguity this caused was sometimes intentional, such as when a character would be used slightly differently on a terminal link or in a data stream.
[src:ascii/ascii] Probably the most influential single device affecting the interpretation of these characters was the Teletype Model 33 ASR, which was a printing terminal with an available paper tape reader/punch option.
[src:ascii/ascii] Paper tape was a very popular medium for long-term program storage until the 1980s, less costly and in some ways less fragile than magnetic tape.
[src:ascii/ascii] In particular, the Teletype Model 33 machine assignments for codes 17 (control-Q, DC1, also known as XON), 19 (control-S, DC3, also known as XOFF), and 127 (delete) became *de facto* standards.
[src:ascii/ascii] The Model 33 was also notable for taking the description of control-G (code 7, BEL, meaning audibly alert the operator) literally, as the unit contained an actual bell which it rang when it received a BEL character.
[src:ascii/ascii] When a Teletype 33 ASR equipped with the automatic paper tape reader received a control-S (XOFF, an abbreviation for transmit off), it caused the tape reader to stop; receiving control-Q (XON, transmit on) caused the tape reader to resume.
[src:ascii/ascii] This so-called flow control technique became adopted by several early computer operating systems as a "handshaking" signal warning a sender to stop transmission because of impending buffer overflow; it persists to this day in many systems as a manual output control technique.
[src:ascii/ascii] On some systems, control-S retains its meaning, but control-Q is replaced by a second control-S to resume output.
[src:ascii/ascii] The 33 ASR also could be configured to employ control-R (DC2) and control-T (DC4) to start and stop the tape punch; on some units equipped with this function, the corresponding control character lettering on the keycap above the letter was TAPE and TAPE respectively.
[src:ascii/ascii] The Teletype could not move its typehead backwards, so it did not have a key on its keyboard to send a BS (backspace).
[src:ascii/ascii] Instead, there was a key marked RUB OUT that sent code 127 (DEL).
[src:ascii/ascii] The purpose of this key was to erase mistakes in a manually-input paper tape: the operator had to push a button on the tape punch to back it up, then type the rubout, which punched all holes and replaced the mistake with a character that was intended to be ignored.
[src:ascii/ascii] Teletypes were commonly used with the less-expensive computers from Digital Equipment Corporation (DEC); these systems had to use what keys were available, and thus the DEL character was assigned to erase the previous character.
[src:ascii/ascii] Because of this, DEC video terminals (by default) sent the DEL character for the key marked "Backspace" while the separate key marked "Delete" sent an escape sequence; many other competing terminals sent a BS character for the backspace key.
[src:ascii/ascii] The assumption that no key sent a BS character allowed Ctrl+H to be used for other purposes, such as the "help" prefix command in GNU Emacs.
[src:ascii/ascii] Many more of the control characters have been assigned meanings quite different from their original ones.
[src:ascii/ascii] The "escape" character (ESC, code 27), for example, was intended originally to allow sending of other control characters as literals instead of invoking their meaning, an "escape sequence".
[src:ascii/ascii] This is the same meaning of "escape" encountered in URL encodings, C language strings, and other systems where certain characters have a reserved meaning.
[src:ascii/ascii] Over time this interpretation has been co-opted and has eventually been changed.
[src:ascii/ascii] In modern usage, an ESC sent *to* the terminal usually indicates the start of a command sequence, which can be used to address the cursor, scroll a region, set/query various terminal properties, and more.
[src:ascii/ascii] They are usually in the form of a so-called "ANSI escape code" (often starting with a "Control Sequence Introducer", "CSI", "ESC [") from ECMA-48 (1972) and its successors.
[src:ascii/ascii] Some escape sequences do not have introducers, like the "Reset to Initial State", "RIS" command "ESC c".
[src:ascii/ascii] In contrast, an ESC read *from* the terminal is most often used as an out-of-band character used to terminate an operation or special mode, as in the TECO and vi text editors.
[src:ascii/ascii] In graphical user interface (GUI) and windowing systems, ESC generally causes an application to abort its current operation or to exit (terminate) altogether.
[src:ascii/ascii] The reapplication of some control characters to new meanings created problems when transferring "plain text" files between systems.
[src:ascii/ascii] The best example of this is the newline problem in various operating systems.
[src:ascii/ascii] Teletype machines required that a line of text be terminated with a "carriage return" (to move the printhead to the beginning of the line) followed by a "line feed" (to advance the paper by one line).
[src:ascii/ascii] The name "carriage return" comes from the fact that, on a manual typewriter, the carriage holding the paper moves while the typebars that strike the ribbon remain stationary.
[src:ascii/ascii] The entire carriage must be pushed to the right ("returned") in order to position the paper for the next line.
[src:ascii/ascii] DEC operating systems (OS/8, RT-11, RSX-11, RSTS, TOPS-10, etc.) stored both characters at the end of each line in textual files, as needed by Teletype machines.
[src:ascii/ascii] When so-called "glass TTYs" were introduced (later called CRTs or "dumb terminals"), they followed the same logic, expecting the same CR and LF characters.
[src:ascii/ascii] When Gary Kildall created CP/M, he was inspired by some of the command line interface conventions used in DEC's RT-11 operating system.
[src:ascii/ascii] Until the introduction of IBM PC DOS in 1981, IBM had no influence in this, because their 1970s operating systems used EBCDIC encoding instead of ASCII and they were oriented toward punch-card input and line printer output on which the concept of "carriage return" was meaningless.
[src:ascii/ascii] IBM's PC DOS (also marketed as MS-DOS by Microsoft) inherited the CRLF convention by virtue of being loosely based on CP/M, and Windows, in turn, inherited it from MS-DOS.
[src:ascii/ascii] Placing CR and LF at the end of each line in a plain text document or data stream reflects what terminals and printers needed to receive, to display that material.
[src:ascii/ascii] Multics introduced an innovation: it used only one character (LF), to represent the end of the line in stored files and in data streams.
[src:ascii/ascii] Upon output, the tty driver converts the LF to CRLF, so files can be printed to a terminal without needing a command to explicitly convert the file format.
[src:ascii/ascii] Unix and Unix-like systems adopted this design from Multics, as did Amiga systems.
[src:ascii/ascii] UNIX documents say "newline" or "NL" to refer to the line terminator.
[src:ascii/ascii] Contrarily, the Radio Shack TRS-80, Apple DOS, Apple ProDOS, and classic Mac OS used a lone carriage return (CR) to terminate lines.
[src:ascii/ascii] Apple's later operating system, Mac OS X (now called macOS) is based on Unix, so it uses line feed (LF).
[src:ascii/ascii] To enable communication between all these systems, the Telnet protocol defined a "Network Virtual Terminal" (NVT), wherein a single text format (ASCII with CR-LF line endings) was used for transmission and each system converted to/from its own native representation.
[src:ascii/ascii] The File Transfer Protocol adopted the Telnet protocol, including the Network Virtual Terminal, for transmitting commands and for transferring textual files (known as "ASCII mode").
[src:ascii/ascii] The World Wide Web's HTTP uses a modified NVT: the standard allows lone CR and LF characters but requires that each be interpreted as an NVT CRLF.
[src:ascii/ascii] Complexity arose in network-facing systems that didn't follow the NVT mechanism, such as some version control systems.
[src:ascii/ascii] Bugs sometimes expose a system's native implementation to other systems on the Internet, causing data corruption.
[src:ascii/ascii] The PDP-6 monitor, and its PDP-10 successor TOPS-10, used control-Z (SUB) as an end-of-file indication for input from a terminal.
[src:ascii/ascii] Some operating systems such as CP/M tracked file length only in units of disk blocks, and used control-Z to mark the end of the actual text in the file.
[src:ascii/ascii] For these reasons, EOF, or end-of-file, was used colloquially and conventionally as a three-letter acronym for control-Z instead of SUBstitute.
[src:ascii/ascii] The end-of-text character (ETX), also known as control-C, was inappropriate for a variety of reasons, while using control-Z as the control character to end a file is analogous to the letter Z's position at the end of the alphabet, and serves as a very convenient mnemonic aid.
[src:ascii/ascii] A historically common and still prevalent convention uses the ETX character convention to interrupt and halt a program via an input data stream, usually from a keyboard.
[src:ascii/ascii] The Unix terminal driver uses the end-of-transmission character (EOT), also known as control-D, to indicate the end of a data stream.
[src:ascii/ascii] In the C programming language, and in Unix conventions, the null character is used to terminate text strings; such null-terminated strings can be known in abbreviation as ASCIZ or ASCIIZ, where here Z stands for "zero".
[src:ascii/ascii] Other representations might be used by specialist equipment, for example ISO 2047 graphics or hexadecimal numbers.
[src:ascii/ascii] At the time of adoption, the codes 20hex to 7Ehex would cause the printing of a visible character (a glyph), and thus were designated "printable characters".
[src:ascii/ascii] These codes represent letters, digits, punctuation marks, and a few miscellaneous symbols.
[src:ascii/ascii] There are 95 printable characters in total.
[src:ascii/ascii] The empty space between words, as produced by the space bar of a keyboard, is character code 20hex.
[src:ascii/ascii] Since the space character is visible in printed text it considered a "printable character", even though it is unique in having no visible glyph.
[src:ascii/ascii] It is listed in the printable character table, as per the ASCII standard, instead of in the control character table.
[src:ascii/ascii] Code 7Fhex corresponds to the non-printable "delete" (DEL) control character and is listed in the control character table.
[src:ascii/ascii] Earlier versions of ASCII used the up arrow instead of the caret (5Ehex) and the left arrow instead of the underscore (5Fhex).
[src:ascii/ascii] ASCII was first used commercially during 1963 as a seven-bit teleprinter code for American Telephone & Telegraph's TWX (TeletypeWriter eXchange) network.
[src:ascii/ascii] TWX originally used the earlier five-bit ITA2, which was also used by the competing Telex teleprinter system.
[src:ascii/ascii] Bob Bemer introduced features such as the escape sequence.
[src:ascii/ascii] His British colleague Hugh McGregor Ross helped to popularize this work – according to Bemer, "so much so that the code that was to become ASCII was first called the *Bemer–Ross Code* in Europe".
[src:ascii/ascii] Because of his extensive work on ASCII, Bemer has been called "the father of ASCII".
[src:ascii/ascii] On March 11, 1968, US President Lyndon B.
[src:ascii/ascii] ASCII was the most common character encoding on the World Wide Web until December 2007, when the UTF-8 encoding surpassed it; UTF-8 is backward compatible with ASCII.
[src:ascii/ascii] As computer technology spread throughout the world, different standards bodies and corporations developed many variations of ASCII to facilitate the expression of non-English languages that used Roman-based alphabets.
[src:ascii/ascii] One could class some of these variations as "ASCII extensions", although some misuse that term to represent all variants, including those that do not preserve ASCII's character-map in the 7-bit range.
[src:ascii/ascii] Furthermore, the ASCII extensions have also been mislabelled as ASCII.
[src:ascii/ascii] From early in its development, ASCII was intended to be just one of several national variants of an international character code standard.
[src:ascii/ascii] Almost every country needed an adapted version of ASCII, since ASCII suited the needs of only the US and a few other countries.
[src:ascii/ascii] For example, Canada had its own version that supported French characters.
[src:ascii/ascii] Many other countries developed variants of ASCII to include non-English letters (e.g. é, ñ, ß, Ł), currency symbols (e.g. £, ¥), etc.
[src:ascii/ascii] It would share most characters in common, but assign other locally useful characters to several code points reserved for "national use".
[src:ascii/ascii] ISO/IEC 646, like ASCII, is a 7-bit character set.
[src:ascii/ascii] It does not make any additional codes available, so the same code points encoded different characters in different countries.
[src:ascii/ascii] C trigraphs were created to solve this problem for ANSI C, although their late introduction and inconsistent implementation in compilers limited their use.
[src:ascii/ascii] Many programmers kept their computers on ASCII, so plain-text in Swedish, German etc.
[src:ascii/ascii] (for example, in e-mail or Usenet) contained "{, }" and similar variants in the middle of words, something those programmers got used to.
[src:ascii/ascii] For example, a Swedish programmer mailing another programmer asking if they should go for lunch, could get "N{ jag har sm|rg}sar" as the answer, which should be "Nä jag har smörgåsar" meaning "No I've got sandwiches".
[src:ascii/ascii] In Japan and Korea, still as of the 2020s, a variation of ASCII is used, in which the backslash (5C hex) is rendered as ¥ (a Yen sign, in Japan) or ₩ (a Won sign, in Korea).
[src:ascii/ascii] This means that, for example, the file path C:\Users\Smith is shown as C:¥Users¥Smith (in Japan) or C:₩Users₩Smith (in Korea).
[src:ascii/ascii] In Europe, teletext character sets, which are variants of ASCII, are used for broadcast TV subtitles, defined by World System Teletext and broadcast using the DVB-TXT standard for embedding teletext into DVB transmissions.
[src:ascii/ascii] In the case that the subtitles were initially authored for teletext and converted, the derived subtitle formats are constrained to the same character sets.
[src:ascii/ascii] Eventually, as 8-, 16-, and 32-bit (and later 64-bit) computers began to replace 12-, 18-, and 36-bit computers as the norm, it became common to use an 8-bit byte to store each character in memory, providing an opportunity for extended, 8-bit relatives of ASCII.
[src:ascii/ascii] In most cases these developed as true extensions of ASCII, leaving the original character-mapping intact, but adding additional character definitions after the first 128 (i.e., 7-bit) characters.
[src:ascii/ascii] ASCII itself remained a seven-bit code: the term "extended ASCII" has no official status.
[src:ascii/ascii] For some countries, 8-bit extensions of ASCII were developed that included support for characters used in local languages (for example, ISCII for India and VISCII for Vietnam).
[src:ascii/ascii] Even for markets where it was not necessary to add many characters to support additional languages, manufacturers of early home computer systems often developed their own 8-bit extensions of ASCII to include additional characters, such as box-drawing characters, semigraphics, and video game sprites.
[src:ascii/ascii] Often, these additions also replaced control characters (index 0 to 31, as well as index 127) with even more platform-specific extensions.
[src:ascii/ascii] In other cases, the extra bit was used for some other purpose, such as toggling inverse video; this approach was used by ATASCII, an extension of ASCII developed by Atari.
[src:ascii/ascii] Most ASCII extensions are based on ASCII-1967 (the current standard), but some extensions are instead based on the earlier ASCII-1963.
[src:ascii/ascii] For example, PETSCII, which was developed by Commodore International for their 8-bit systems, is based on ASCII-1963.
[src:ascii/ascii] Likewise, many Sharp MZ character sets are based on ASCII-1963.
[src:ascii/ascii] IBM defined code page 437 for the IBM PC, replacing the control characters with graphic symbols such as smiley faces, and mapping additional graphic characters to the upper 128 positions.
[src:ascii/ascii] Digital Equipment Corporation developed the Multinational Character Set (DEC-MCS) for use in the popular VT220 terminal as one of the first extensions designed more for international languages than for block graphics.
[src:ascii/ascii] Apple defined Mac OS Roman for the Macintosh and Adobe defined the PostScript Standard Encoding for PostScript; both sets contained "international" letters, typographic symbols and punctuation marks instead of graphics, more like modern character sets.
[src:ascii/ascii] The ISO/IEC 8859 standard (derived from the DEC-MCS) provided a standard that most systems copied (or at least were based on, when not copied exactly).
[src:ascii/ascii] A popular further extension designed by Microsoft, Windows-1252 (often mislabeled as ISO-8859-1), added the typographic punctuation marks needed for traditional text printing.
[src:ascii/ascii] ISO-8859-1, Windows-1252, and the original 7-bit ASCII were the most common character encoding methods on the World Wide Web until 2008, when UTF-8 overtook them.
[src:ascii/ascii] ISO/IEC 4873 introduced 32 additional control codes defined in the 80–9F hexadecimal range, as part of extending the 7-bit ASCII encoding to become an 8-bit system.
[src:ascii/ascii] Unicode and the ISO/IEC 10646 Universal Character Set (UCS) have a much wider array of characters and their various encoding forms have begun to supplant ISO/IEC 8859 and ASCII rapidly in many environments.
[src:ascii/ascii] While ASCII is limited to 128 characters, Unicode and the UCS support more characters by separating the concepts of unique identification (using natural numbers called *code points*) and encoding (to 8-, 16-, or 32-bit binary formats, called UTF-8, UTF-16, and UTF-32, respectively).
[src:ascii/ascii] ASCII was incorporated into the Unicode (1991) character set as the first 128 symbols, so the 7-bit ASCII characters have the same numeric codes in both sets.
[src:ascii/ascii] This allows UTF-8 to be backward compatible with 7-bit ASCII, as a UTF-8 file containing only ASCII characters is identical to an ASCII file containing the same sequence of characters.
[src:ascii/ascii] Even more importantly, forward compatibility is ensured as software that recognizes only 7-bit ASCII characters as special and does not alter bytes with the highest bit set (as is often done to support 8-bit ASCII extensions such as ISO-8859-1) will preserve UTF-8 data unchanged.
[src:ascii/page] The **exclamation mark** **!** (also known as **exclamation point** in American English) is a punctuation mark usually used after an interjection, an exclamation, a noise to indicate strong feelings (e.g. surprise, humour, anger), a loud sound (e.g.
[src:ascii/page] The exclamation mark often marks the end of a sentence.
[src:ascii/page] A bare exclamation mark (with nothing before or after) is frequently used in warning signs.
[src:ascii/page] The exclamation mark likely came from the word *io*, used to show joy and surprise.
[src:ascii/page] Writers made a set of changes to *io* that made it become the exclamation mark.
[src:ascii/page] In the mid-14th century the Italian writer Iacopo Alpoleio da Urbisaglia created the exclamation mark since he was bothered when readers read emotional text without emotion.
[src:ascii/page] In the 14th century, the exclamation mark was named the *punctus admirativus/exclamativus*, coming from a text by the writer Iacopo Alpoleio da Urbisaglia.
[src:ascii/page] About fifty years later, the writer Coluccio Salutati used the exclamation mark in his writing.
[src:ascii/page] This spread its use to England, where the name *punctus admirativus/exclamativus* was translated to "point of admiration/exclamation".
[src:ascii/page] Later, people began to name it the "point/note/sign of admiration/exclamation".
[src:ascii/page] The difference between "admiration" and "exclamation" ended in the 19th century, when people found it unneeded.
[src:ascii/page] In the 17th century the name "exclamation mark" became popular.
[src:ascii/page] Linguists say that the exclamation mark comes from a Latin exclamation of joy, namely *io*, similar to "hooray".
[src:ascii/page] Writers would write *io* at the end of sentences to show happiness.
[src:ascii/page] Over time, these writers made a set of changes to *io*, such as placing the "I" above the "O", and making the "O" smaller until it turned into a dot.
[src:ascii/page] This set of changes turned *io* to the exclamation mark.
[src:ascii/page] The exclamation mark comes from the mid-14th century, when the writer Iacopo Alpoleio da Urbisaglia made it.
[src:ascii/page] The linguist Florence Hazrat says he "was really annoyed" that people read emotional text with no emotion, leading him to create the exclamation mark.
[src:ascii/page] His early exclamation mark looked similar to the modern one, it was a period with an apostrophe above it.
[src:ascii/page] It was used to show emotions such as admiration and surprise.
[src:ascii/page] In his text, he named it the *punctus admirativus/exclamativus*, although this name fell out of use.
[src:ascii/page] The exclamation mark was next used by the writer Coluccio Salutati in the early 15th century, which led to its common usage.
[src:ascii/page] Shortly after, English printing press operators started to use the exclamation mark in their printing to give emphasis to sentences.
[src:ascii/page] Older or portable typewriters often did not have the exclamation mark; to replicate it, users typed a period, backspaced, and then typed an apostrophe.
[src:ascii/page] Now obsolete, the name *ecphoneme* was documented in the early 20th century.
[src:ascii/page] In the 1950s, secretarial dictation and typesetting manuals in America referred to the mark as "bang", perhaps from comic books – where the ! appeared in dialogue bubbles to represent a gun being fired, although the nickname probably emerged from letterpress printing.
[src:ascii/page] This "bang" usage is behind the names of the interrobang, an unconventional typographic character, and the shebang, a feature of Unix computer systems.
[src:ascii/page] In the printing world, the exclamation mark can be called a screamer, a gasper, a slammer, a dog's cock, or a startler.
[src:ascii/page] Programmers originally called the exclamation mark by its full name or "shriek", but Unix popularized the "bang" name.
[src:ascii/page] For example, the password communicated in the spoken phrase "Your password is em-zero-pee-aitch-bang-en-three" is `m0ph!n3`.
[src:ascii/page] The exclamation mark is mainly used in languages that use the Latin alphabet, although usage slightly varies.
[src:ascii/page] It has also been adopted in languages written in other scripts, such as languages written with Cyrillic or Arabic scripts, Chinese characters, and Devanagari.
[src:ascii/page] A sentence ending in an exclamation mark may represent an exclamation (such as "Wow!"), interjection ("Boo!"), imperative ("Stop!"), or astonishment or surprise: ("They were the footprints of a gigantic hound!").
[src:ascii/page] Informally, exclamation marks may be repeated for additional emphasis ("That's great!!!"), but this practice is generally considered unacceptable in formal prose.
[src:ascii/page] The exclamation mark is sometimes used in conjunction with the question mark.
[src:ascii/page] This can be in protest or astonishment ("Out of all places, the squatter-camp?!"); a few writers replace this with a single, unconventional punctuation mark, the interrobang, which is the combination of a question mark and an exclamation mark.
[src:ascii/page] Overly frequent use of the exclamation mark is generally considered poor writing, as it distracts the reader and decreases the mark's significance.
[src:ascii/page] Some authors, most notably Tom Wolfe, are known for their unashamedly liberal use of the exclamation mark.
[src:ascii/page] In comic books, the very frequent use of exclamation marks is common—see Comics, below.
[src:ascii/page] For information on the use of spaces after an exclamation mark, see the discussion of spacing after a period.
[src:ascii/page] Several studies have shown that women use exclamation marks more than men do.
[src:ascii/page] One study suggests that, in addition to other uses, exclamation marks may also function as markers of friendly interaction, for example, by making "Hi!" or "Good luck!" seem friendlier than simply "Hi." or "Good luck." (with periods).
[src:ascii/page] However, use of exclamation marks in contexts that are not unambiguously positive can be misinterpreted as indicating hostility.
[src:ascii/page] In English writing and often subtitles, a **(!)** symbol (an exclamation mark within parentheses) implies that a character has made an obviously sarcastic comment e.g.: "Ooh, a sarcasm detector.
[src:ascii/page] That's a *really useful* invention(!)" It is also used to indicate surprise at one's own experience or statement.
[src:ascii/page] In French, as well as marking exclamations or indicating astonishment, the exclamation mark is commonly used to mark orders or requests: *Viens ici !* (English: 'Come here!').
[src:ascii/page] When available, a 'narrow no-break space' (*espace fine insécable*) is used between the last word and the exclamation mark in European French.
[src:ascii/page] If not, a regular non-breaking space (*espace insécable*) is currently used.
[src:ascii/page] In Canadian French, either no space is used or a small space (*espace fine insécable*) is inserted if available.
[src:ascii/page] One can also combine an exclamation mark with a question mark at the end of a sentence where appropriate.
[src:ascii/page] Cantonese has not historically used dedicated punctuation marks, rather relying on grammatical markers to denote the end of a statement.
[src:ascii/page] Usage of exclamation marks is common in written Mandarin and in some Yue speaking regions.
[src:ascii/page] The Canton and Hong Kong regions, however, generally refused to accept the exclamation mark as it was seen as carrying with it unnecessary and confusing Western connotations.
[src:ascii/page] However, an exclamation mark, including in some written representations of colloquy in Cantonese, can be used informally to indicate strong feelings.
[src:ascii/page] In Modern Greek, the exclamation mark (Θαυμαστικό, *thavmastikó*) has been introduced from Latin scripts and is used identically, although without the reluctance seen in English usage.
[src:ascii/page] A minor grammatical difference is that, while a series of interjections each employ an exclamation mark (e.g., Ωχ! Αχ!, [*Ōch!
[src:ascii/page] Oh!']), an interjection should only be separated from an extended exclamation by a comma (e.g., Ωχ, ξέχασα το μάτι της κουζίνας ανοιχτό!, *Ōch, xéchasa to máti tīs kouzínas anoichtó!*, 'Oops!
[src:ascii/page] In Hungarian, an exclamation mark is put at the end of exclamatory, imperative or prohibitive sentences, and sentences expressing a wish (e.g.
[src:ascii/page] *De szép!* – 'How beautiful!', *A fűre lépni tilos!* – 'Keep off the grass', *Bárcsak sikerülne a tervem!* – 'If only my plan would work out.').
[src:ascii/page] The use of the exclamation mark is also needed when addressing someone and the addressing is a separate sentence.
[src:ascii/page] (typically at the beginning of letters, e.g.
[src:ascii/page] Greetings are also typically terminated with an exclamation mark (e.g.
[src:ascii/page] In Solomon Islands Pidgin, the phrase may be between admiration marks.
[src:ascii/page] In Spanish, a sentence or clause ending in an exclamation mark must also begin with an inverted exclamation mark (the same also applies to the question mark): *¿Estás loco? ¡Casi la matas!*, 'Are you crazy?
[src:ascii/page] As in British English, a bracketed exclamation mark may be used to indicate irony or surprise at a statement: *Dice que esta noche no va a salir de fiesta (!)*, 'He said that he's not going to a party tonight(!).' Such use is not matched by an inverted opening exclamation mark.
[src:ascii/page] In Turkish, an exclamation mark is used after a sentence or phrase for emphasis, and is common following both commands and the addressees of such commands.
[src:ascii/page] For example, in the *Ordular! İlk hedefiniz Akdenizdir, ileri!* ('Armies!
[src:ascii/page] Your first target is the Mediterranean') order by Atatürk, *ordular* ('the armies') constitute the addressee.
[src:ascii/page] It is further used in parentheses, *(!)*, after a sentence or phrase to indicate irony or sarcasm: *Çok iyi bir iş yaptın (!)*, 'You've done a very good job – Not!'.
[src:ascii/page] In Limbu, an exclamation mark (᥄) is used after a Limbu sentence or phrase for emphasis, and is common following both commands and the addressees of such commands.
[src:ascii/page] For example, in the Limbu sentence ᤐᤚᤢ᥄ ᤄᤨᤘᤑ ᤂᤥᤆᤌᤙ Mediterranean, ᤚᤦᤛᤅ᥄ (*Paṡu!
[src:ascii/page] Ghōwapha khōcathaśa Mediterranean, ṡausaṅa!*, 'Armies!
[src:ascii/page] Your first target is the *Mediterranean*!').
[src:ascii/page] It is further used in parentheses, (᥄), after a sentence or phrase to indicate irony or sarcasm: ᤖᤥᤂᤌ ᤔᤚᤗ ᤐᤤ ᤊᤇ ᤃᤦᤄ (᥄) (*Rōkhatha maṡala pai yancha gaugha (!)*, 'You did a very good job — Not!').
[src:ascii/page] In Khoisan languages, and the International Phonetic Alphabet, a symbol that looks like the exclamation mark is used as a letter to indicate the postalveolar click sound (represented as *q* in Zulu orthography).
[src:ascii/page] In Unicode, this letter is properly coded as U+01C3 ǃ LATIN LETTER RETROFLEX CLICK and distinguished from the common punctuation symbol U+0021 !
[src:ascii/page] EXCLAMATION MARK to allow software to deal properly with word breaks.
[src:ascii/page] The exclamation mark has sometimes been used as a phonetic symbol to indicate that a consonant is ejective.
[src:ascii/page] More commonly, this is represented by an apostrophe, or a superscript glottal stop symbol (U+02C0 ˀ MODIFIER LETTER GLOTTAL STOP).
[src:ascii/page] Although not part of dictionary words, exclamation marks appear in some brand names and trade names, including Yum!
[src:ascii/page] Brands (parent of fast food chains like Taco Bell and KFC), Web services Yahoo! and Joomla!, and the online game Kahoot!, although some media style guides, including those of Reuters and *The Economist*, omit such marks from trade names.
[src:ascii/page] It appears in the titles of some stage and screen works, especially comedies and musicals; examples include the game show *Jeopardy!*; the '60s musical TV show *Shindig!*; musicals *Oklahoma!*, *Mamma Mia!*, *Oliver!*, and *Oh!
[src:ascii/page] Calcutta!*; and movies *Airplane!* and *Moulin Rouge!*.
[src:ascii/page] In the 1970s, the exclamation mark fell out of favor for major musicals, but has remained common in ironic or parody titles.
[src:ascii/page] In the 2016 United States presidential campaign, Republican candidate Jeb Bush used "Jeb!" as his campaign logo.
[src:ascii/page] The English town of Westward Ho!, named after the novel by Charles Kingsley, is the only place name in the United Kingdom that officially contains an exclamation mark.
[src:ascii/page] There is a town in Quebec called Saint-Louis-du-Ha!
[src:ascii/page] Ha!, which is spelled with two exclamation marks.
[src:ascii/page] The city of Hamilton, Ohio, changed its name to Hamilton! in 1986, but neither the United States Board on Geographic Names nor mapmakers Rand McNally recognized the change.
[src:ascii/page] The city of Ostrava, Czech Republic, changed its logotype to Ostrava!!! in 2008.
[src:ascii/page] Exclamation marks are used to emphasize a precautionary statement.
[src:ascii/page] On warning signs, an exclamation mark is often used to draw attention to a warning of danger, hazards, and the unexpected.
[src:ascii/page] These signs are common in hazardous environments or on potentially dangerous equipment.
[src:ascii/page] A common type of this warning is a yellow triangle with a black exclamation mark, but a white triangle, with a red border is common on European road warning signs.
[src:ascii/page] In most cases, a pictogram indicating the nature of the hazard is enclosed in the triangle but an exclamation mark may be used instead as a generic symbol; a plate beneath identifies the hazard.
[src:ascii/page] The *Zirkel* monogram of a German *Studentenverbindung* includes an exclamation mark if the society is still active.
[src:ascii/page] In mathematics the symbol represents the factorial operation.
[src:ascii/page] The expression *n*! means "the product of the integers from 1 to n", for example, 4!
[src:ascii/page] Two exclamation marks (*n*!!) is the double factorial, which is a smaller value.
[src:ascii/page] In front of a number (!*n*) represents the subfactorial.
[src:ascii/page] It is used to represent the uniqueness quantifier.
[src:ascii/page] In linear logic, the exclamation mark denotes one of the modalities that control weakening and contraction.
[src:ascii/page] In computing, the exclamation mark is ASCII character 33 (21 in hexadecimal).
[src:ascii/page] Due to its availability even on early computers, the character was used for many purposes.
[src:ascii/page] The name given to "!" by programmers varies according to their background, though it was very common to give it a short name to make reading code aloud easier.
[src:ascii/page] In the UK, the term pling was popular in the earlier days of computing, whilst in the United States, the term shriek was used.
[src:ascii/page] It is claimed that these word usages were invented in the US and *shriek* is from Stanford or MIT; however, *shriek* for the ! sign is found in the *Oxford English Dictionary* dating from the 1860s.
[src:ascii/page] Many computer languages using C-style syntax use "!" for logical negation; `!A` means "not A", and `A != B` means "A is not equal to B".
[src:ascii/page] This negation principle has spread to ordinary language; for example, the word "!clue" is used as a synonym for "no-clue" or "clueless".
[src:ascii/page] The symbol in formal logic for negation is `¬` but, as this symbol is not present as standard on most keyboards, the C convention has spread informally to other contexts.
[src:ascii/page] In Cascading Style Sheets (CSS), "!" is used as a delimiter in the `!important` flag, which alters the rules selecting declarations.
[src:ascii/page] The flag means "important", rather than "not important", which usage of "!" might suggest.
[src:ascii/page] In Hypertext Markup Language (HTML), "!" appears as part of the Document type declaration as, for example, `<!DOCTYPE html>`.
[src:ascii/page] It also forms part of the HTML opening comment delimiter `<!−−`.
[src:ascii/page] Early email systems also used the exclamation mark as a separator character between hostnames for routing information, usually referred to as "bang path" notation.
[src:ascii/page] In the IRC protocol, a user's nickname and ident are separated by an exclamation mark in the hostmask assigned to them by the server.
[src:ascii/page] In UNIX scripting (typically for UNIX shell or Perl), "!" is usually used after a "#" in the first line of a script, the interpreter directive, to tell the OS what program to use to run the script.
[src:ascii/page] `#!` is usually called a "hash-bang" or shebang.
[src:ascii/page] A similar convention for PostScript files calls for the first line to begin with `%!`, called "percent-bang".
[src:ascii/page] An exclamation mark starts history expansions in many Unix shells such as bash and tcsh where `!!` executes the previous command and `!*` refers to all the arguments from the previous command.
[src:ascii/page] Acorn RISC OS uses filenames starting with pling to create an application directory: for instance, a file called `!Run` is executed when the folder containing it is double-clicked (holding down shift prevents this).
[src:ascii/page] There is also `!Boot` (executed the first time the application containing it comes into view of the filer), `!Sprites` (icons), `!Help`, and others.
[src:ascii/page] In APL, `!x` is used for the factorial of x (backwards from math notation), and also for the binomial coefficient: `k!n` means ${\tbinom {n}{k}}$ or *n*!⁄*k*!(*n*–*k*)!.
[src:ascii/page] BBC BASIC used the exclamation mark as an indirection operator, equivalent to PEEK and POKE of four bytes at once.
[src:ascii/page] BCPL, the precursor of C, used "!" for pointer and array indirection: `!P` is equivalent to `*P` in C, and `P!3` is equivalent to `P[3]` in C.
[src:ascii/page] In the Xbase family of programming languages, which includes dBase and FoxPro, an exclamation mark, when used as part of an expression, indicates negation.
[src:ascii/page] At the start of a line of code, it is a synonym for RUN (which executes an external program).
[src:ascii/page] In the Haskell programming language, "!" is used to express strictness.
[src:ascii/page] In the Kotlin programming language, "!!" ("double-bang") is the not-null assertion operator, used to override null safety so as to allow a null pointer exception.
[src:ascii/page] In the ML programming language (including Standard ML and OCaml), "!" is the operator to get the value out of a "reference" data structure.
[src:ascii/page] In the Raku programming language, the "!" twigil is used to access private attributes or methods in a class (like `class Person { has $!name; }` or `self!private-method;`).
[src:ascii/page] In the Scheme, Julia, and Ruby programming languages, "!" is conventionally the suffix for functions and special forms that mutate their input.
[src:ascii/page] In the Swift programming language, a type followed by "!" denotes an "implicitly unwrapped optional", an option type where the compiler does not enforce safe unwrapping.
[src:ascii/page] The "!" operator "force unwraps" an option type, causing an error if it is nil.
[src:ascii/page] In Geek Code version 3, "!" is used before a letter to denote that the geek refuses to participate in the topic at hand.
[src:ascii/page] In some cases, it has an alternate meaning, such as *G!* denoting a geek of no qualifications, *!d* denoting not wearing any clothes, *P!* denoting not being allowed to use Perl, and so on.
[src:ascii/page] They all share some negative connotations, however.
[src:ascii/page] `!` is used to denote changed lines in `diff` output in the context format.
[src:ascii/page] In the unified format, changes to a single line are denoted as an addition and deletion.
[src:ascii/page] The exclamation mark can be used in video games to signify that a character is startled or alarmed.
[src:ascii/page] In the *Metal Gear* and *Paper Mario* series, an exclamation mark appears over enemies' heads when they notice the player.
[src:ascii/page] In massively multiplayer online games such as *World of Warcraft*, an exclamation mark hovering over a character's head is often used to indicate that they are offering a quest for the player to complete.
[src:ascii/page] In *Dota 2*, an exclamation mark is shown above the head of a unit if it is killed by means not granting enemies experience or gold (if it is "denied").
[src:ascii/page] In the 2005 arcade dance simulation game *In the Groove 2*, there is a song titled "!" (also referred to as "bang") by the artist Onyx.
[src:ascii/page] In Internet culture, especially where leet is used, multiple exclamation marks may be affixed with the numeral "1", as in *!!!!!!111*.
[src:ascii/page] The notation originates from a common error: when typing multiple exclamation points quickly, the typist may fail to hold the ⇧ Shift1 combination that produces the exclamation mark on many keyboard layouts.
[src:ascii/page] This error, first used intentionally as a joke in the leet linguistic community, is now an accepted form of exclamation in leet and derivative dialects such as Lolspeak.
[src:ascii/page] Some utterances include further substitutions, for example "!!!111oneeleven".
[src:ascii/page] In fandom and fanfiction, ! is used to signify a defining quality in a character, usually signifying an alternative interpretation of a character from a canonical work.
[src:ascii/page] Examples of this would be "Romantic!Draco" or "Vampire!Harry" from the *Harry Potter* fandom.
[src:ascii/page] It is also used to clarify the current persona of a character with multiple identities or appearances, such as to distinguish "Armor!Al" from "Human!Al" in a work based on *Fullmetal Alchemist*.
[src:ascii/page] The origin of this usage is unknown, although it is hypothesized to have originated with certain *Teenage Mutant Ninja Turtles* action figures; for example, "Football Player!
[src:ascii/page] This tends to lead to exaggerated speech, in line with the other hyperboles common in comic books.
[src:ascii/page] A portion of the motivation, however, was simply that a period might disappear in the printing process used at the time, whereas an exclamation point would likely remain recognizable even if there was a printing glitch.
[src:ascii/page] For a short period, Stan Lee, as editor-in-chief of Marvel Comics, attempted to curb their overuse by a short-lived ban on exclamation marks altogether, which led to an inadvertent lack of ending punctuation in many sentences.
[src:ascii/page] Maggin once accidentally signed his name with an exclamation due to the habit of using them when writing comic scripts; it became his professional name from then on.
[src:ascii/page] Similarly, comic artist Scott Shaw has used the exclamation point after his name throughout his career.
[src:ascii/page] In comic books and comics in general, a large exclamation point is often used near or over a character's head to indicate surprise.
[src:ascii/page] A question mark can similarly be used to indicate confusion.
[src:ascii/page] In chess annotation, "!" denotes a good move, "!!" denotes an excellent move, "?!" denotes a dubious move, and "!?" denotes an interesting, risky move.
[src:ascii/page] ('Annotation' here refers to post-match commentary use).
[src:ascii/page] Standard chess notation used to record game moves does not use the exclamation mark.
[src:ascii/page] In *Scrabble*, an exclamation mark written after a word is used to indicate its presence in the Official Tournament and Club Word List but its absence from the *Official Scrabble Players Dictionary*, usually because the word has been judged offensive.
[src:ascii/page] Exclamation points or asterisks can be used on scorecards to denote a "great defensive play".
[src:ascii/page] (pronounced "Chk Chk Chk") uses exclamation points as its name.
[src:ascii/page] In 2008, the pop-punk band Panic! at the Disco dropped the exclamation point in its name; this became the "most-discussed topic on [fan] message boards around the world".
[src:ascii/page] In 2009, the exclamation mark was re-inserted following the band's split.
[src:ascii/page] The band Bomb the Music Industry! utilizes an exclamation mark in its name, as well as several album and song titles and promotional material.
[src:ascii/page] Examples include their songs "(Shut) Up The Punx!!!" and the album *Adults!!!: Smart!!!
[src:ascii/page] American musician Pink stylizes her stage name "P!NK", and uses three exclamation points in the subtitle of her 2010 release, *Greatest Hits...
[src:ascii/page] The exclamation mark was included in the title of Dinah Shore's TV series, *Dinah!* The exclamation mark was later the subject of a bitter argument between Elaine Benes and her boyfriend, Jake Jarmel, in the *Seinfeld* episode, "The Sniffing Accountant".
[src:ascii/page] Elaine got upset with Jake for not putting an exclamation mark at the end of a message about her friend having a baby.
